---
import Layout from '~/layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import DocsShell from '~/components/widgets/DocsShell.astro';

const metadata = {
  title: 'Docs — Aitroop',
};
---

<Layout metadata={metadata}>
  <DocsShell current="index">
    <h1>Aitroop documentation</h1>
    <p class="lead">
      Aitroop is an AI agent platform. You build <strong>Apps</strong> — saved workflows with a form,
      a goal, and a defined output — by talking to the agent in chat. Apps run on demand or on a
      schedule, and produce typed artifacts you can share, download, or chain.
    </p>

    <h2>The one-paragraph version</h2>
    <p>
      Open a chat. Say <em>"Create an app that…"</em>. The agent asks 1–5 clarifying questions, designs
      the App (form fields, stages, output format, required Skills and Connects), saves it via the API,
      and gives you the App ID. You then run the App from your library — fill the form, click Run, get
      a typed Artifact. Or attach a Schedule and it runs automatically.
    </p>

    <div class="callout">
      <strong>Apps are built conversationally, not by clicking through menus.</strong> If you've used
      ChatGPT, you already know how to use Aitroop — you just add the phrase "as an app" at the end of your
      request when you want to keep it.
    </div>

    <h2>Where to start</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/docs/quickstart">Quickstart</a></strong> — 15 minutes, end-to-end. Sign in,
        build an App by talking to the agent, run it, schedule it. <strong>Read this first.</strong>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/docs/concepts">Core concepts</a></strong> — the App JSON schema, all 11 AppInput
        types, the 3 stage types, the <code>{`{{field_id}}`}</code> template syntax. Reference companion to the Quickstart.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/docs/chat">Chat mode</a></strong> and <strong><a href="/docs/apps">Apps</a></strong> —
        the two surfaces in detail.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/docs/skills">Skills</a></strong>, <strong><a href="/docs/connects">Connects</a></strong>,
        <strong><a href="/docs/schedules">Schedules</a></strong>, <strong><a href="/docs/artifacts">Artifacts</a></strong> —
        deep dives. Read when you need the depth.
      </li>
    </ol>

    <h2>What an App looks like</h2>
    <p>A real (slightly simplified) App definition:</p>
    <div class="code-block" style="line-height:1.7;">
{`{`}<br/>
&nbsp;&nbsp;"name":     "Company Brief",<br/>
&nbsp;&nbsp;"icon":     "🏢",<br/>
&nbsp;&nbsp;"input_schema": [<br/>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;{`{`} "id": "company_name", "type": "text", "required": true {`}`},<br/>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;{`{`} "id": "tone", "type": "select",<br/>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"options": [{`{`} "label": "Executive", "value": "exec" {`}`}, ...] {`}`}<br/>
&nbsp;&nbsp;],<br/>
&nbsp;&nbsp;"stages": [<br/>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;{`{`} "id": "research", "stage_type": "agent",<br/>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"goal": "Research <span style="color:var(--aw-color-primary)">{`{{company_name}}`}</span> and write a brief<br/>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;in a <span style="color:var(--aw-color-primary)">{`{{tone}}`}</span> tone...",<br/>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"artifact_defs": [<br/>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;{`{`} "id": "brief", "format": "markdown" {`}`}<br/>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;] {`}`}<br/>
&nbsp;&nbsp;],<br/>
&nbsp;&nbsp;"resources": {`{`} "skills": ["web-search"], "connects": [] {`}`}<br/>
{`}`}
    </div>
    <p>
      You don't write this. The agent does. But knowing the shape makes the Quickstart easier to follow —
      you'll see the agent constructing exactly this kind of object as you describe what you want.
    </p>

    <h2>Three things you can do in Aitroop</h2>

    <h3>1. Build an App from a chat</h3>
    <p>
      Say <em>"Create an app that…"</em>. The agent activates the App Builder skill, asks clarifying questions,
      designs the JSON, validates it, and saves via <code>POST /api/apps</code>. You get an App in your library.
    </p>

    <h3>2. Run an App</h3>
    <p>
      Click the App in your library. Fill the form. Click <strong>Run</strong>. The platform spins up a fresh
      isolated sandbox, runs each stage in order, and produces the declared artifacts. You preview, download,
      or chain them to other Apps.
    </p>

    <h3>3. Schedule an App</h3>
    <p>
      From the App page, attach a Schedule: a cron expression, pre-filled inputs, and a delivery target
      (email, Slack, Drive, webhook). The App runs automatically on the cron and the artifact gets delivered.
    </p>

    <h2>If you get stuck</h2>
    <p>
      The agent itself is the fastest help. Open a chat and ask "How do I…?" — it has the App Builder skill
      loaded and knows every part of the platform. Or <a href="/contact">talk to us</a>.
    </p>

    <div class="next-up">
      <span class="label">Start here</span>
      <a href="/docs/quickstart">Quickstart — build your first App in 15 min</a>
    </div>
  </DocsShell>
</Layout>
